1
00:00:30,114 --> 00:00:32,414
(CROWD CHEERING AND WHISTLING)

2
00:00:35,286 --> 00:00:37,746
He was the phenomenon of the '20s.

3
00:00:38,414 --> 00:00:41,759
When you think, at the time, he was
as well-known as Lindbergh,

4
00:00:41,834 --> 00:00:42,924
it's really quite astonishing.

5
00:00:43,252 --> 00:00:44,632
(CROWD CHEERING)

6
00:00:46,297 --> 00:00:49,547
<i>His story reflected
the nature of our civilization,</i>

7
00:00:50,176 --> 00:00:51,886
<i>the character of our times,</i>

8
00:00:52,386 --> 00:00:54,346
yet it was also one man's story.

9
00:00:54,930 --> 00:00:58,730
And all the themes of our culture
were there.

10
00:00:58,809 --> 00:01:01,439
Heroism, will, things like that.

11
00:01:01,812 --> 00:01:04,652
But when you look back on it,
it was very strange.

12
00:01:07,985 --> 00:01:12,525
<i>Well, it is ironic to see
how quickly he has faded from memory,</i>

13
00:01:13,282 --> 00:01:15,622
considering what
an astounding record he made.

14
00:01:16,619 --> 00:01:21,749
He was, of course, very amusing, but at
the same time touched a nerve in people,

15
00:01:23,292 --> 00:01:27,172
perhaps in a way in which
they would prefer not to be touched.

16
00:01:28,506 --> 00:01:30,336
It certainly is a very bizarre story.

17
00:01:30,966 --> 00:01:32,836
(CHARLESTON PLAYING)

18
00:01:45,981 --> 00:01:47,781
NARRATOR: <i>The year is 1928.</i>

19
00:01:48,818 --> 00:01:53,198
<i>America, enjoying a decade
of unequalled prosperity, has gone wild.</i>

20
00:01:53,781 --> 00:01:57,031
<i>The Jazz Age, it is called.
The rhythms are syncopated,</i>

21
00:01:57,409 --> 00:02:00,159
<i>the morals are looser,
the liquor is cheaper,</i>

22
00:02:00,663 --> 00:02:02,043
<i>when you can get it.</i>

23
00:02:03,499 --> 00:02:07,089
<i>It is a time of diverse heroes
and madcap stunts,</i>

24
00:02:07,878 --> 00:02:10,548
<i>of speakeasies and flamboyant parties.</i>

25
00:02:11,882 --> 00:02:14,972
<i>One typical party occurs
at the Long Island estate</i>

26
00:02:15,052 --> 00:02:17,472
<i>of Mr. and Mrs. Henry Porter Sutton,</i>

27
00:02:17,638 --> 00:02:19,968
<i>socialites, patrons of the arts.</i>

28
00:02:20,766 --> 00:02:24,556
<i>Politicians and poets rub elbows
with the cream of high society.</i>

29
00:02:25,563 --> 00:02:28,403
<i>Present at the party is Scott Fitzgerald,</i>

30
00:02:28,607 --> 00:02:32,237
<i>who is to cast perspective on the '20s
for all future generations.</i>

31
00:02:32,945 --> 00:02:38,195
<i>He writes in his notebook about a curious
little man named Leon Selwyn or Zelman,</i>

32
00:02:38,659 --> 00:02:41,119
<i>who seemed clearly to be an aristocrat,</i>

33
00:02:41,203 --> 00:02:44,173
<i>and extolled the very rich
as he chatted with socialites.</i>

34
00:02:44,790 --> 00:02:47,630
<i>He spoke adoringly of Coolidge
and the Republican party,</i>

35
00:02:47,918 --> 00:02:50,088
<i>all in an upper-class Boston accent.</i>

36
00:02:51,046 --> 00:02:53,296
<i>"An hour later," writes Fitzgerald,</i>

37
00:02:53,382 --> 00:02:57,262
<i>"I was stunned to see the same man
speaking with the kitchen help."</i>

38
00:02:57,761 --> 00:03:01,771
<i>"Now, he claimed to be a Democrat
and his accent seemed to be coarse,</i>

39
00:03:02,099 --> 00:03:03,929
<i>"as if he were one of the crowd."</i>

40
00:03:04,560 --> 00:03:07,610
<i>It is the first small notice
taken of Leonard Zelig.</i>

41
00:03:10,149 --> 00:03:12,109
<i>Florida, one year later.</i>

42
00:03:12,359 --> 00:03:16,109
<i>An odd incident occurs
at the New York Yankees' training camp.</i>

43
00:03:16,780 --> 00:03:18,620
<i>Journalists, anxious as always</i>

44
00:03:18,699 --> 00:03:21,659
<i>to immortalize the exploits
of the great home-run hitters,</i>

45
00:03:21,994 --> 00:03:26,214
<i>notice a strange new player waiting
his turn at bat after Babe Ruth.</i>

46
00:03:27,041 --> 00:03:29,791
<i>He is listed on the roster as Lou Zelig,</i>

47
00:03:30,085 --> 00:03:31,955
<i>but no one on the team has heard of him.</i>

48
00:03:33,172 --> 00:03:36,632
<i>Security guards are called,
and he is escorted from the premises.</i>

49
00:03:37,718 --> 00:03:41,098
<i>It appears as a small item
in the next day's newspaper.</i>

50
00:03:46,644 --> 00:03:49,234
<i>(CHICAGO THAT TODDLIN' TOWN</i> PLAYING)

51
00:03:49,438 --> 00:03:51,858
<i>Chicago, Illinois, that same year.</i>

52
00:03:52,274 --> 00:03:55,074
<i>There is a private party
at a speakeasy on the South Side.</i>

53
00:03:55,819 --> 00:04:00,279
<i>People from the most respectable
walks of life dance and drink bathtub gin.</i>

54
00:04:06,330 --> 00:04:10,000
<i>Present that evening
was Calvin Turner, a waiter.</i>

55
00:04:10,876 --> 00:04:13,496
A lotta customers,
a lotta gangsters came in the place.

56
00:04:13,671 --> 00:04:16,011
'Cause they always good tippers
and take good care of us,

57
00:04:16,173 --> 00:04:17,973
and of course we try to take
care of our customers.

58
00:04:18,550 --> 00:04:22,470
But on this particular night, I looked over
and here's a strange guy comin' in.

59
00:04:22,846 --> 00:04:25,556
I'd never seen him before,
so I asked one of the others, I say,

60
00:04:25,641 --> 00:04:27,851
<i>"John, you know this guy?
You ever seen him?"</i>

61
00:04:27,935 --> 00:04:30,595
<i>So he looks.
"No, I ain't never seen him before."</i>

62
00:04:30,854 --> 00:04:33,524
<i>"I don't know who he is,
but I know he's a tough-looking hombre."</i>

63
00:04:34,191 --> 00:04:37,071
<i>So I looked over, and next thing,
the guy had disappeared.</i>

64
00:04:37,528 --> 00:04:41,778
I don't know where he went to, but about
this time, the music usually gets started.

65
00:04:42,366 --> 00:04:44,696
And the band started... (SCATTING)
Playin', and I looked,

66
00:04:44,785 --> 00:04:47,865
and here's a colored guy,
a colored boy playin' trumpet.

67
00:04:48,497 --> 00:04:49,957
Man, he was playin' back.

68
00:04:50,624 --> 00:04:52,504
<i>I looked at the guy
and said "Well, my goodness.</i>

69
00:04:53,002 --> 00:04:56,632
<i>"He looks just like that gangster,
but the gangster was white</i>

70
00:04:56,714 --> 00:04:58,134
<i>"and this guy is black."</i>

71
00:04:58,549 --> 00:05:00,719
<i>So I don't know what's...
What's happening.</i>

72
00:05:02,886 --> 00:05:05,716
NARRATOR:
<i>New York City. It is several months later.</i>

73
00:05:06,473 --> 00:05:10,943
<i>Police are investigating the disappearance
of a clerk named Leonard Zelig.</i>

74
00:05:11,562 --> 00:05:14,732
<i>Both his landlady and his employer
have reported him missing.</i>

75
00:05:15,774 --> 00:05:19,194
<i>They tell police he was
an odd little man who kept to himself.</i>

76
00:05:20,237 --> 00:05:23,867
<i>Only two clues are found
in Zelig's Greenwich Village flat.</i>

77
00:05:24,992 --> 00:05:28,252
<i>One, a photograph of Zelig
with Eugene O'Neill,</i>

78
00:05:29,580 --> 00:05:31,710
<i>and one of him as Pagliacci.</i>

79
00:05:36,086 --> 00:05:39,466
<i>Acting on a tip, they trace
his whereabouts to Chinatown,</i>

80
00:05:39,923 --> 00:05:44,223
<i>where, in the rear of a Chinese
establishment, a strange-looking Oriental</i>

81
00:05:44,553 --> 00:05:47,723
<i>who fits the description
of Leonard Zelig is discovered.</i>

82
00:05:48,599 --> 00:05:51,889
<i>Suspicious, the detectives
try to pull off his disguise,</i>

83
00:05:52,436 --> 00:05:55,266
<i>but it is not a disguise,
and a fight breaks out.</i>

84
00:05:56,231 --> 00:05:59,821
<i>He is removed by force,
and taken to Manhattan Hospital.</i>

85
00:06:00,736 --> 00:06:05,566
<i>In the ambulance, he rants and curses
in what sounds like authentic Chinese.</i>

86
00:06:06,200 --> 00:06:08,660
<i>He is restrained with a straitjacket.</i>

87
00:06:10,621 --> 00:06:13,171
<i>When he emerges from the car
20 minutes later,</i>

88
00:06:13,457 --> 00:06:17,167
<i>incredibly, he is no longer Chinese,
but Caucasian.</i>

89
00:06:18,253 --> 00:06:22,173
<i>Bewildered interns place him
in the emergency room for observation.</i>

90
00:06:23,384 --> 00:06:29,434
<i>At 7:00 a.m., Dr. Eudora Fletcher,
a psychiatrist, makes her usual rounds.</i>

91
00:06:30,140 --> 00:06:33,390
When I first heard about this
emergency case that had been brought in,

92
00:06:33,936 --> 00:06:35,726
I didn't think anything peculiar.

93
00:06:36,188 --> 00:06:40,398
And when I first laid eyes on him,
it was a bit strange,

94
00:06:40,651 --> 00:06:43,741
because I mistook him for a doctor.

95
00:06:44,238 --> 00:06:47,028
<i>He had a very professional
demeanor about him.</i>

96
00:06:48,075 --> 00:06:49,575
NARRATOR: <i>As a young psychiatrist,</i>

97
00:06:49,660 --> 00:06:52,450
<i>Eudora Fletcher is fascinated
by Leonard Zelig.</i>

98
00:06:53,163 --> 00:06:56,583
<i>She convinces the conservative staff
at the hospital to allow her</i>

99
00:06:56,667 --> 00:06:59,127
<i>to pursue a study of the new admission.</i>

100
00:06:59,461 --> 00:07:03,341
- FLETCHER: <i>What do you do?</i>
- ZELIG: <i>Oh, me? I'm a psychiatrist.</i>

101
00:07:03,507 --> 00:07:05,757
- FLETCHER: <i>Oh, yes?</i>
- ZELIG: <i>Yes, yes, I work</i>

102
00:07:06,051 --> 00:07:08,181
<i>mostly with delusional paranoids.</i>

103
00:07:08,512 --> 00:07:11,352
- FLETCHER: <i>Tell me about it.</i>
- ZELIG: <i>Oh, there's not much to tell. I...</i>

104
00:07:12,558 --> 00:07:14,178
<i>I work mostly on the Continent,</i>

105
00:07:14,268 --> 00:07:17,018
<i>and I've written quite
a few psychoanalytic papers.</i>

106
00:07:17,354 --> 00:07:20,194
<i>I've studied a great deal.
I worked with Freud in Vienna.</i>

107
00:07:20,524 --> 00:07:23,034
<i>Yes, we broke over
the concept of penis envy.</i>

108
00:07:23,527 --> 00:07:25,817
<i>Freud felt that it
should be limited to women.</i>

109
00:07:27,531 --> 00:07:29,911
FLETCHER: <i>It's not that
he was making any sense at all.</i>

110
00:07:30,367 --> 00:07:33,657
<i>It was just a conglomeration
of psychological double-talk</i>

111
00:07:34,163 --> 00:07:37,923
<i>that he had apparently heard, or perhaps
was familiar with through reading.</i>

112
00:07:38,375 --> 00:07:41,545
<i>The funny thing was
that his delivery was quite fluid,</i>

113
00:07:41,879 --> 00:07:43,514
<i>and might have been really
quite convincing</i>

114
00:07:43,589 --> 00:07:45,299
<i>to someone who did not know any better.</i>

115
00:07:46,717 --> 00:07:48,587
NARRATOR: <i>Who was this Leonard Zelig</i>

116
00:07:48,719 --> 00:07:51,679
<i>that seemed to create
such diverse impressions everywhere?</i>

117
00:07:52,723 --> 00:07:56,360
<i>All that was known of him was that
he was the son of a Yiddish actor</i>

118
00:07:56,435 --> 00:07:59,515
<i>named Morris Zelig,
whose performance as Puck</i>

119
00:07:59,813 --> 00:08:04,943
<i>in the Orthodox version of</i> A Midsummer
Night's Dream, <i>was coolly received.</i>

120
00:08:06,111 --> 00:08:10,781
<i>The elder Zelig's second marriage is
marked by constant violent quarrelling,</i>

121
00:08:11,241 --> 00:08:14,751
<i>so much so, that although
the family lives over a bowling alley,</i>

122
00:08:15,078 --> 00:08:17,748
<i>it is the bowling alley
that complains of noise.</i>

123
00:08:19,249 --> 00:08:22,749
<i>As a boy, Leonard is
frequently bullied by anti-Semites.</i>

124
00:08:23,420 --> 00:08:27,550
<i>His parents, who never take his part
and blame him for everything,</i>

125
00:08:27,758 --> 00:08:29,838
<i>side with the anti-Semites.</i>

126
00:08:30,260 --> 00:08:32,850
<i>They punish him often
by locking him in a dark closet.</i>

127
00:08:33,597 --> 00:08:36,807
<i>When they are really angry,
they get into the closet with him.</i>

128
00:08:38,268 --> 00:08:41,098
<i>On his deathbed,
Morris Zelig tells his son</i>

129
00:08:41,647 --> 00:08:44,687
<i>that life is a meaningless
nightmare of suffering,</i>

130
00:08:45,442 --> 00:08:48,702
<i>and the only advice
he gives him is to save string.</i>

131
00:08:50,155 --> 00:08:52,445
<i>Though brother Jack
has a nervous breakdown,</i>

132
00:08:52,908 --> 00:08:55,658
<i>and sister Ruth becomes
a shoplifter and alcoholic,</i>

133
00:08:56,286 --> 00:08:58,746
<i>Leonard Zelig appears
to have adjusted to life.</i>

134
00:09:00,374 --> 00:09:02,504
<i>Somehow, he seems to have coped.</i>

135
00:09:02,876 --> 00:09:07,086
<i>And then, suddenly,
increasingly strange behavior.</i>

136
00:09:10,801 --> 00:09:12,971
<i>Fascinated by the Zelig phenomenon,</i>

137
00:09:13,053 --> 00:09:15,643
<i>Dr. Fletcher arranges
a series of experiments</i>

138
00:09:15,889 --> 00:09:18,559
<i>and invites the skeptical staff
to observe.</i>

139
00:09:19,643 --> 00:09:24,153
<i>With the doctors watching,
Zelig becomes a perfect psychiatrist.</i>

140
00:09:25,691 --> 00:09:27,784
<i>When two Frenchmen are brought in,</i>

141
00:09:27,859 --> 00:09:31,489
<i>Zelig assumes their characters
and speaks reasonable French.</i>

142
00:09:33,407 --> 00:09:37,697
<i>In the company of a Chinese person,
he begins to develop oriental features.</i>

143
00:09:39,079 --> 00:09:41,749
<i>By now, word has gotten out to the press,</i>

144
00:09:41,832 --> 00:09:46,632
<i>and a public thirsting for thrills
and novelty is immediately captivated.</i>

145
00:09:50,841 --> 00:09:55,851
<i>The clamor is so great that Dr. Allan
Sindell is forced to issue a statement.</i>

146
00:09:56,054 --> 00:09:58,604
We're just beginning
to realize the dimensions

147
00:09:58,682 --> 00:10:02,522
of what could be the scientific
medical phenomenon of the age,

148
00:10:02,603 --> 00:10:04,353
and possibly of all time.

149
00:10:05,105 --> 00:10:07,355
NARRATOR:
<i>Fresh stories roll off the press every day</i>

150
00:10:07,441 --> 00:10:09,651
<i>about Zelig and his puzzling condition.</i>

151
00:10:10,777 --> 00:10:14,197
<i>Although the doctors claim
to have the situation in hand,</i>

152
00:10:14,573 --> 00:10:16,913
<i>no two can agree on a diagnosis.</i>

153
00:10:17,659 --> 00:10:19,670
I'm convinced
that it's glandular in nature

154
00:10:19,745 --> 00:10:22,115
and although there's no evidence now
of any misfunction,

155
00:10:22,748 --> 00:10:25,748
I'm sure that further tests
will show a problem in the secretions.

156
00:10:26,251 --> 00:10:28,881
I'm certain it's something
he picked up from eating Mexican food.

157
00:10:30,047 --> 00:10:32,417
This manifestation
is neurological in origin.

158
00:10:33,050 --> 00:10:36,510
Now, this patient
is suffering from a brain tumor,

159
00:10:36,970 --> 00:10:40,220
and I should not be surprised if,
within several weeks, he died.

160
00:10:40,474 --> 00:10:43,354
Now, we have not as yet
been able to locate the tumor,

161
00:10:43,685 --> 00:10:45,685
but we're still looking.

162
00:10:47,230 --> 00:10:49,730
NARRATOR:
<i>Ironically, within two weeks' time,</i>

163
00:10:50,067 --> 00:10:53,357
<i>it is Dr. Birsky himself
who dies of a brain tumor.</i>

164
00:10:54,029 --> 00:10:55,909
<i>Leonard Zelig is fine.</i>

165
00:10:57,282 --> 00:11:00,202
<i>Throughout the weeks
of testing and speculation,</i>

166
00:11:00,535 --> 00:11:04,205
<i>Eudora Fletcher begins to feel
that the patient might be suffering</i>

167
00:11:04,539 --> 00:11:06,669
<i>not from a physiological disorder,</i>

168
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:08,590
<i>but from a psychological one.</i>

169
00:11:09,586 --> 00:11:12,296
<i>It is Zelig's unstable make-up,
she suggests,</i>

170
00:11:12,756 --> 00:11:14,966
<i>that accounts for his metamorphoses.</i>

171
00:11:15,425 --> 00:11:18,715
<i>The governing board of doctors
is hostile to her notion.</i>

172
00:11:19,262 --> 00:11:23,812
<i>They conclude that Zelig's malady can be
traced to poor alignment of the vertebrae.</i>

173
00:11:24,768 --> 00:11:28,938
<i>Tests prove them wrong, and cause
a temporary problem for the patient.</i>

174
00:11:32,484 --> 00:11:35,954
<i>Now, the press and public
hang on every bit of news,</i>

175
00:11:36,113 --> 00:11:38,783
<i>thoroughly absorbed
in the real-life drama.</i>

176
00:11:40,033 --> 00:11:42,203
MAN: (ON RADIO) <i>The continuing saga
of the strange creature</i>

177
00:11:42,285 --> 00:11:43,785
<i>at Manhattan Hospital goes on.</i>

178
00:11:43,954 --> 00:11:46,334
<i>This morning, doctors report,
experiments were conducted</i>

179
00:11:46,456 --> 00:11:50,286
<i>and several women of varying types were
placed in close proximity to the subject,</i>

180
00:11:50,419 --> 00:11:53,259
<i>but no change occurred,
leading authorities to conclude</i>

181
00:11:53,380 --> 00:11:55,720
<i>that the phenomenon
does not occur with women.</i>

182
00:11:56,133 --> 00:11:59,723
<i>Later today, doctors will be experimenting
with a midget and a chicken.</i>

183
00:12:07,519 --> 00:12:10,113
MAN: (ON NEWSREEL) <i>Leonard Zelig
continues to astound scientists</i>

184
00:12:10,188 --> 00:12:11,818
<i>at New York's Manhattan Hospital,</i>

185
00:12:11,982 --> 00:12:14,117
<i>where numerous tests have led nowhere</i>

186
00:12:14,192 --> 00:12:17,202
<i>in determining the nature of
this astonishing manifestation.</i>

187
00:12:17,779 --> 00:12:21,909
<i>He is confronted by two overweight men
at the request of the doctors.</i>

188
00:12:22,325 --> 00:12:26,995
<i>As the men discuss their obesity,
an initially reticent Zelig joins in,</i>

189
00:12:27,330 --> 00:12:31,330
<i>swelling himself to
a miraculous 250 pounds.</i>

190
00:12:31,960 --> 00:12:34,670
<i>Next, in the presence of two Negro men,</i>

191
00:12:34,880 --> 00:12:37,510
<i>Zelig rapidly becomes one himself.</i>

192
00:12:37,799 --> 00:12:39,839
<i>What will they think of next?</i>

193
00:12:40,844 --> 00:12:45,064
<i>Meanwhile, Americans all over
have their own reactions.</i>

194
00:12:46,349 --> 00:12:49,019
I wish I could be
Lenny Zelig, the changing man.

195
00:12:49,269 --> 00:12:52,559
I'd be different people, and maybe
someday my wishes will come true.

196
00:12:53,398 --> 00:12:57,778
Leonard Zelig is
one of the finest gentlemen

197
00:12:57,861 --> 00:13:00,201
in the United States of America!

198
00:13:00,363 --> 00:13:03,073
He is the cat's pajamas!

199
00:13:04,201 --> 00:13:06,002
NARRATOR:
<i>Trying a new approach, Dr. Fletcher</i>

200
00:13:06,077 --> 00:13:08,037
<i>places the subject under hypnosis.</i>

201
00:13:09,372 --> 00:13:12,792
FLETCHER:
<i>Tell me why you assume the characteristics</i>

202
00:13:12,876 --> 00:13:14,376
<i>of the person you're with.</i>

203
00:13:15,295 --> 00:13:17,415
ZELIG: (SLEEPILY) <i>It's safe.</i>

204
00:13:17,923 --> 00:13:19,633
FLETCHER: <i>What do you mean?
What do you mean, "safe"?</i>

205
