00:40:33,181 --> 00:40:35,351
I ask the rabbi the meaning of life.

625
00:40:37,477 --> 00:40:39,147
He tells me the meaning of life,

626
00:40:40,647 --> 00:40:42,227
but he tells it to me in Hebrew.

627
00:40:44,192 --> 00:40:45,572
I don't understand Hebrew.

628
00:40:47,696 --> 00:40:51,066
Then he wants to charge me $600
for Hebrew lessons.

629
00:40:53,326 --> 00:40:56,406
NARRATOR: <i>Dr. Fletcher's therapy
consists of a two-pronged attack.</i>

630
00:40:57,289 --> 00:41:02,379
<i>In the trance state, the personality will
be deeply probed and then restructured.</i>

631
00:41:03,170 --> 00:41:06,550
<i>In the conscious state,
she will provide love and affection,</i>

632
00:41:06,923 --> 00:41:09,183
<i>unconditional positive regard.</i>

633
00:41:34,034 --> 00:41:36,244
You will be completely honest.

634
00:41:36,745 --> 00:41:38,245
You're in a deep trance.

635
00:41:38,955 --> 00:41:43,245
You will become, not who you think
I want you to be, but you'll be yourself.

636
00:41:44,711 --> 00:41:46,551
Now, how do you feel about it here?

637
00:41:50,008 --> 00:41:51,548
It's the worst.

638
00:41:52,594 --> 00:41:54,304
I hate the country.

639
00:41:55,430 --> 00:41:57,970
I hate the grass and the mosquitoes.

640
00:41:59,893 --> 00:42:02,983
And cooking... Your cooking is terrible.

641
00:42:04,105 --> 00:42:05,685
Your pancakes...

642
00:42:06,399 --> 00:42:08,989
They're... I dump them in the garbage
when you're not looking.

643
00:42:09,945 --> 00:42:13,155
- Uh-huh.
- And the jokes you try and tell when...

644
00:42:13,990 --> 00:42:15,830
When you think you're amusing,

645
00:42:16,743 --> 00:42:20,463
they're long and pointless,
there's no end to them.

646
00:42:21,206 --> 00:42:23,956
I see. And what else?

647
00:42:27,128 --> 00:42:28,708
I wanna go to bed with you.

648
00:42:32,551 --> 00:42:35,301
Oh... That surprises me.

649
00:42:36,137 --> 00:42:38,137
I didn't think you liked me very much.

650
00:42:38,974 --> 00:42:40,314
I love you.

651
00:42:42,519 --> 00:42:43,729
You do?

652
00:42:45,105 --> 00:42:48,015
You're very sweet, 'cause you're...

653
00:42:48,316 --> 00:42:50,686
You're not as clever as you think you are.

654
00:42:51,319 --> 00:42:53,109
You're all mixed up,

655
00:42:53,780 --> 00:42:57,370
and nervous, and you're the worst cook.

656
00:42:57,993 --> 00:42:59,663
Those pancakes...

657
00:43:00,120 --> 00:43:01,870
Oh, I love you.

658
00:43:02,998 --> 00:43:04,498
I wanna take care of you.

659
00:43:06,710 --> 00:43:08,340
No more pancakes.

660
00:43:17,721 --> 00:43:22,271
FLETCHER: <i>I started out by trying
to use Leonard to make my reputation,</i>

661
00:43:22,976 --> 00:43:25,646
<i>and then I found that
I had very strong feelings for him.</i>

662
00:43:26,354 --> 00:43:28,490
<i>I never thought I was attractive.</i>

663
00:43:28,565 --> 00:43:30,685
<i>I never had a real romance.</i>

664
00:43:30,859 --> 00:43:34,279
<i>Charles Koslow was the type of man
my mother felt I should marry.</i>

665
00:43:41,036 --> 00:43:43,456
NARRATOR: <i>Feeling more confident
every day with her patient,</i>

666
00:43:43,538 --> 00:43:45,788
<i>Dr. Fletcher takes him
for a cautious outing,</i>

667
00:43:46,291 --> 00:43:49,461
<i>an afternoon at
her sister's house in nearby Teaneck.</i>

668
00:43:50,462 --> 00:43:54,552
<i>Meryl Fletcher is an aviatrix,
a fine professional pilot.</i>

669
00:43:55,342 --> 00:43:57,892
<i>Eudora Fletcher is an amateur pilot,</i>

670
00:43:58,053 --> 00:44:02,893
<i>and the afternoon is spent relaxing
and retelling old flying experiences.</i>

671
00:44:05,435 --> 00:44:07,988
<i>As the weeks pass, Zelig is encouraged</i>

672
00:44:08,063 --> 00:44:11,113
<i>to open up more and more,
to give his own opinions.</i>

673
00:44:11,733 --> 00:44:15,243
<i>What was guarded at first
soon becomes expansive.</i>

674
00:44:16,029 --> 00:44:19,569
ZELIG: <i>I hated my stepmother,
and I don't care who knows it.</i>

675
00:44:22,494 --> 00:44:24,084
<i>I love baseball.</i>

676
00:44:24,537 --> 00:44:28,287
<i>You know, it doesn't have to mean
anything, it's just very beautiful to watch.</i>

677
00:44:31,753 --> 00:44:34,803
<i>I'm a Democrat. I always was a Democrat.</i>

678
00:44:37,092 --> 00:44:39,552
<i>Is it okay if I don't agree with you
about that recording?</i>

679
00:44:39,761 --> 00:44:43,721
- FLETCHER: <i>Of course.</i>
- ZELIG: <i>I mean, Brahms is just always</i>

680
00:44:44,307 --> 00:44:46,387
<i>too melodramatic for me.</i>

681
00:44:49,479 --> 00:44:52,907
<i>You have to be your own person
and make your own moral choices,</i>

682
00:44:52,982 --> 00:44:58,572
<i>even when they do require real courage,
otherwise you're like a robot, or a lizard.</i>

683
00:45:01,241 --> 00:45:02,991
<i>Are you really gonna
get married to that lawyer?</i>

684
00:45:03,576 --> 00:45:05,746
<i>I... I would much rather you didn't.</i>

685
00:45:07,497 --> 00:45:11,037
<i>No, I don't agree.
I think this guy Mussolini is a loser.</i>

686
00:45:13,837 --> 00:45:16,297
<i>Uh... Are we ever gonna make love?</i>

687
00:45:17,632 --> 00:45:21,092
NARRATOR: <i>It has been three months, and
the board wishes to examine the patient.</i>

688
00:45:21,803 --> 00:45:24,603
<i>Dr. Fletcher says
Zelig is not ready to leave the premises.</i>

689
00:45:25,014 --> 00:45:27,024
<i>The doctors agree to visit him there.</i>

690
00:45:27,475 --> 00:45:29,885
<i>The date is set, four days hence.</i>

691
00:45:30,812 --> 00:45:34,942
<i>If progress is insufficient,
she will be removed from the case.</i>

692
00:45:37,652 --> 00:45:40,662
I was very nervous,
because in his waking state

693
00:45:40,989 --> 00:45:43,369
he never remembered
anything from his trance state,

694
00:45:44,200 --> 00:45:48,410
and I wondered if there could be some
way of locking these two things together.

695
00:45:49,122 --> 00:45:54,502
And then I also was worried
that if he was with strong personalities,

696
00:45:54,669 --> 00:45:56,379
he might lose his personality.

697
00:45:57,630 --> 00:46:00,130
NARRATOR:
<i>Sunday at noon. The doctors arrive.</i>

698
00:46:00,842 --> 00:46:04,012
<i>They are greeted
by Eudora Fletcher and Leonard Zelig</i>

699
00:46:04,387 --> 00:46:05,847
<i>and are shown around the grounds.</i>

700
00:46:06,598 --> 00:46:08,942
<i>Though Dr. Fletcher is tense and alert,</i>

701
00:46:09,017 --> 00:46:11,637
<i>Leonard Zelig seems calm and at ease.</i>

702
00:46:12,395 --> 00:46:16,645
<i>Despite the fact that he is surrounded
by physicians, he does not turn into one.</i>

703
00:46:17,901 --> 00:46:21,111
<i>The encounter appears
to be a resounding success,</i>

704
00:46:21,404 --> 00:46:25,034
<i>when Dr. Henry Mayerson comments
innocently about the weather,</i>

705
00:46:25,366 --> 00:46:27,196
<i>saying that it is a nice day.</i>

706
00:46:28,077 --> 00:46:32,617
<i>Zelig tells Dr. Mayerson that
he does not agree that it is a nice day.</i>

707
00:46:34,125 --> 00:46:37,705
<i>Dr. Mayerson is taken aback
at the firmness of Zelig's conviction.</i>

708
00:46:38,630 --> 00:46:42,220
<i>He points out that
the sun is shining and that it is mild.</i>

709
00:46:43,593 --> 00:46:48,563
<i>Zelig, trained to voice his own personal
opinions fearlessly, is too aggressive.</i>

710
00:46:49,057 --> 00:46:51,677
<i>He has been molded
too far in the other direction.</i>

711
00:46:51,976 --> 00:46:53,862
<i>He has become over-opinionated,</i>

712
00:46:53,937 --> 00:46:56,607
<i>and cannot brook
any disagreement with his own views.</i>

713
00:46:58,358 --> 00:47:00,398
I had taken him
too far in the other direction.

714
00:47:01,277 --> 00:47:04,907
He had struck Dr. Mayerson and
several board members with a rake.

715
00:47:05,615 --> 00:47:10,115
This was not what we wanted, and yet
I felt that I had accomplished something.

716
00:47:11,120 --> 00:47:15,290
<i>I felt if I could have him for two more
weeks, I could do some fine-tuning</i>

717
00:47:15,708 --> 00:47:18,838
<i>and turn Leonard Zelig
back into his own man.</i>

718
00:47:30,807 --> 00:47:32,427
MAN: (ON NEWSREEL)
<i>Dr. Eudora Nesbit Fletcher,</i>

719
00:47:32,517 --> 00:47:35,097
<i>the hero, or should we say heroine,
of the hour.</i>

720
00:47:36,104 --> 00:47:39,824
<i>The beautiful and brilliant psychiatrist
never lost faith in her conviction</i>

721
00:47:39,899 --> 00:47:43,489
<i>that Leonard Zelig, the human chameleon,
was suffering from a mental disorder.</i>

722
00:47:44,195 --> 00:47:46,905
<i>Working with her cousin,
cameraman Paul Deghuee,</i>

723
00:47:46,990 --> 00:47:49,530
<i>the doctor managed to keep
a vital record of the proceedings</i>

724
00:47:49,951 --> 00:47:52,791
<i>including rare footage
of Zelig hypnotized.</i>

725
00:47:53,872 --> 00:47:56,962
<i>The patient and his healer have become
fast friends in the process,</i>

726
00:47:57,292 --> 00:48:00,462
<i>and enjoy one another's company
even when she's not working on him.</i>

727
00:48:01,129 --> 00:48:03,969
<i>The result of maintaining
a courageous minority opinion</i>

728
00:48:04,382 --> 00:48:06,842
<i>is a resounding success for psychiatry.</i>

729
00:48:07,093 --> 00:48:09,763
<i>Who says women are just good for sewing?</i>

730
00:48:10,972 --> 00:48:12,392
<i>Now it's on to City Hall,</i>

731
00:48:12,473 --> 00:48:15,063
<i>where the town's newest celebrities are
given the key to the city.</i>

732
00:48:16,311 --> 00:48:18,561
CITY HALL SPEAKER: We're honored
to present this key to New York City

733
00:48:18,646 --> 00:48:19,686
to the two of you.

734
00:48:22,984 --> 00:48:26,534
And, uh... Jimmy Walker
did wanna be here this afternoon

735
00:48:26,696 --> 00:48:29,446
and sing <i>Leonard the Lizard,</i>
but he was just too busy.

736
00:48:33,286 --> 00:48:35,996
MAN: (ON NEWSREEL) <i>After City Hall,
Eudora Fletcher, the beautiful genius</i>

737
00:48:36,331 --> 00:48:38,831
<i>who cured Zelig
of his science-defying condition,</i>

738
00:48:39,167 --> 00:48:42,837
<i>is honored by fellow scientists
at New York's Waldorf-Astoria.</i>

739
00:48:43,046 --> 00:48:45,506
<i>Present are luminaries from
all over the world,</i>

740
00:48:45,590 --> 00:48:47,340
<i>not just in the field of psychiatry,</i>

741
00:48:47,634 --> 00:48:50,854
<i>but physics, biology,
mathematics, and you name it.</i>

742
00:48:51,429 --> 00:48:53,719
<i>Here she is exchanging theories
with Nils Andersen,</i>

743
00:48:53,890 --> 00:48:55,850
<i>the father of modern blood disease.</i>

744
00:48:58,102 --> 00:49:01,652
<i>Later in the week, Dr. Fletcher is again
honored by the greatest city in the world,</i>

745
00:49:01,814 --> 00:49:04,194
<i>as she gets to christen her first ship.</i>

746
00:49:04,275 --> 00:49:07,315
<i>Quite a success story
for a little girl from the backwoods.</i>

747
00:49:08,029 --> 00:49:11,699
MALE NEWSCASTER: <i>Dr. Fletcher has
smashed the bottle, not champagne...</i>

748
00:49:12,367 --> 00:49:15,407
I'm speaking to you from
the home of Mrs. Catherine Fletcher.

749
00:49:15,620 --> 00:49:18,870
She's the mother of Dr. Eudora Fletcher,

750
00:49:18,998 --> 00:49:21,668
the famous psychiatrist
so much in the news these days.

751
00:49:22,043 --> 00:49:24,883
And I'm going to be
asking Mrs. Fletcher to...

752
00:49:25,755 --> 00:49:31,505
To begin with, to tell us something about
what it's like to raise a medical genius.

753
00:49:31,803 --> 00:49:35,723
And I might ask you
about the many sacrifices

754
00:49:35,848 --> 00:49:38,558
that you've made to put your daughter
through medical school.

755
00:49:38,685 --> 00:49:41,029
And could you speak
right into the microphones, please?

756
00:49:41,104 --> 00:49:44,654
Sacrifices, we had none.
John was a stockbroker,

757
00:49:45,066 --> 00:49:48,896
he had plenty of money, and I came
from a wealthy Philadelphia family, so...

758
00:49:49,070 --> 00:49:52,450
Well, I'm sure that your daughter
always wanted to be a doctor,

759
00:49:52,657 --> 00:49:54,027
ever since she could remember.

760
00:49:56,744 --> 00:49:58,084
I don't think so.

761
00:49:58,705 --> 00:50:02,915
I always thought she'd want to be a flier
like her sister Meryl and raise a family.

762
00:50:03,751 --> 00:50:07,921
- But she was a very moody...
- But still, a mother always dreams

763
00:50:08,006 --> 00:50:10,796
for her child to have the kind of success
that your daughter has.

764
00:50:11,259 --> 00:50:14,219
- She was a very difficult girl.
- Well, tell me about your husband.

765
00:50:14,804 --> 00:50:17,104
I understand that
he is a simple businessman.

766
00:50:17,181 --> 00:50:19,181
He must be so thrilled and pleased

767
00:50:19,267 --> 00:50:21,517
to have his daughter
achieve such recognition.

768
00:50:22,937 --> 00:50:26,607
John had problems, depression. He drank.

769
00:50:27,567 --> 00:50:31,737
Well, Mrs. Fletcher, thank you
so much for speaking with us today.

770
00:50:40,872 --> 00:50:42,122
MAN: (ON NEWSREEL) <i>Here at San Simeon,</i>

771
00:50:42,206 --> 00:50:45,626
<i>glorious dreamland of newspaper mogul
William Randolph Hearst,</i>

772
00:50:45,793 --> 00:50:49,463
<i>celebrities from
all walks of society, sun or play.</i>

773
00:50:50,381 --> 00:50:55,301
<i>There's Marie Dressler with Mr. Hearst.
Always a popular guest at San Simeon,</i>

774
00:50:55,762 --> 00:50:58,722
<i>Miss Dressler accepts
a flower from an ardent admirer.</i>

775
00:50:59,974 --> 00:51:02,314
<i>Along with her is Marion Davies.</i>

776
00:51:02,769 --> 00:51:05,899
<i>When she works,
Miss Davies is always dead serious,</i>

777
00:51:06,314 --> 00:51:08,574
<i>but here at this fabulous playground,</i>

778
00:51:08,649 --> 00:51:10,689
<i>she shows us her fun side.</i>

779
00:51:11,986 --> 00:51:16,236
<i>There she is with you-know-who,
Charlie Chaplin, always kidding.</i>

780
00:51:17,658 --> 00:51:20,294
<i>Although New York is 3,000 miles away,</i>

781
00:51:20,369 --> 00:51:24,119
<i>Jimmy Walker somehow appears
through Mr. Hearst's enchanted gateway.</i>

782
00:51:25,458 --> 00:51:27,498
<i>Another New Yorker is Leonard Zelig,</i>

783
00:51:27,960 --> 00:51:32,220
<i>here shown clowning with
