00:53:14,108 --> 00:53:15,898
<i>I'm singin' a song</i>

812
00:53:16,611 --> 00:53:18,361
<i>Just singin' a song</i>

813
00:53:19,113 --> 00:53:21,993
<i>Glory, hallelujah, I told Leonard Zelig</i>

814
00:53:22,200 --> 00:53:24,490
<i>Hey, Len, get ready to call</i>

815
00:53:25,244 --> 00:53:29,424
<i>Just like Humpty Dumpty, I'm ready to fall</i>

816
00:53:29,582 --> 00:53:32,792
<i>I'm sittin' on top of the world</i>

817
00:53:32,960 --> 00:53:36,630
<i>My, my, my, rollin' along</i>

818
00:53:36,923 --> 00:53:39,933
<i>Rollin' along</i>

819
00:53:40,468 --> 00:53:44,558
NARRATOR: <i>Zelig, no longer a chameleon,
is at last his own man.</i>

820
00:53:45,431 --> 00:53:50,651
<i>His point of view on politics, art,
life and love is honest and direct.</i>

821
00:53:51,812 --> 00:53:56,072
<i>Though his taste is described
by many as lowbrow, it is his own.</i>

822
00:53:56,984 --> 00:54:00,074
<i>He is finally an individual,
a human being.</i>

823
00:54:00,154 --> 00:54:02,414
<i>He no longer gives up his own identity</i>

824
00:54:02,490 --> 00:54:05,240
<i>to be a safe and invisible
part of his surroundings.</i>

825
00:54:05,952 --> 00:54:07,372
Oh, his taste wasn't terrible.

826
00:54:07,870 --> 00:54:12,670
He was the kind of man who preferred
watching baseball to reading <i>Moby Dick.</i>

827
00:54:13,000 --> 00:54:16,500
And that got him off on the wrong foot,
or so the legend goes.

828
00:54:18,130 --> 00:54:22,090
It was much more a matter of symbolism.
To the Marxists, he was one thing.

829
00:54:23,803 --> 00:54:27,353
The Catholic Church never
forgave him for the Vatican incident.

830
00:54:29,058 --> 00:54:32,728
The American people, in the throes
of the Depression as they were,

831
00:54:33,688 --> 00:54:38,188
found in him a symbol of possibility,
of self-improvement and self-fulfillment.

832
00:54:38,901 --> 00:54:40,531
And of course, the Freudians had a ball.

833
00:54:40,653 --> 00:54:44,073
They could interpret him
in any way they pleased.

834
00:54:44,573 --> 00:54:47,833
It was all symbolism,
but there were no two intellectuals

835
00:54:47,952 --> 00:54:49,952
who agreed about what it meant.

836
00:54:51,038 --> 00:54:53,538
I don't know if you could call it
a triumph of psychotherapy.

837
00:54:53,624 --> 00:54:56,294
It seems more like
a triumph of aesthetic instincts,

838
00:54:56,377 --> 00:54:59,457
because Dr. Fletcher's
techniques didn't owe anything to

839
00:54:59,755 --> 00:55:01,795
then-current schools of therapy.

840
00:55:02,133 --> 00:55:04,393
But she sensed what was needed
and she provided it,

841
00:55:04,760 --> 00:55:08,140
and that was, in its way,
a remarkable creative accomplishment.

842
00:55:09,098 --> 00:55:11,728
When I think about it,
it seems to me that his story

843
00:55:11,809 --> 00:55:15,149
reflected a lot of
the Jewish experience in America,

844
00:55:15,229 --> 00:55:18,866
the great urge to push in
and to find one's place

845
00:55:18,941 --> 00:55:21,651
and then to assimilate into the culture.

846
00:55:22,069 --> 00:55:24,359
I mean, he wanted
to assimilate like crazy.

847
00:55:24,989 --> 00:55:26,739
<i>(SUNNY SIDE UP</i> PLAYING)

848
00:55:33,414 --> 00:55:37,594
NARRATOR: <i>Eudora Fletcher's life
has also changed from this experience.</i>

849
00:55:38,336 --> 00:55:41,416
<i>For her, fame and recognition
are empty rewards</i>

850
00:55:41,672 --> 00:55:45,432
<i>and do not live up to the adolescent
fantasies that prompted her ambition.</i>

851
00:55:46,594 --> 00:55:49,354
<i>She and her patient have fallen in love,</i>

852
00:55:49,597 --> 00:55:53,847
<i>and it is no surprise when she forsakes
the upwardly mobile attorney Koslow</i>

853
00:55:54,226 --> 00:55:56,936
<i>and announces wedding plans with Zelig.</i>

854
00:55:58,981 --> 00:56:01,821
WOMAN: (SINGING) <i>Now there's one thing
to think of when you're blue</i>

855
00:56:03,319 --> 00:56:06,029
<i>There are others much worse off than you</i>

856
00:56:07,365 --> 00:56:10,525
<i>If a load of trouble should arrive</i>

857
00:56:11,327 --> 00:56:14,787
<i>Laugh and say it's great to be alive</i>

858
00:56:15,456 --> 00:56:18,916
<i>Keep your sunny side up, up</i>

859
00:56:19,043 --> 00:56:22,423
<i>Hide the side that gets blue</i>

860
00:56:23,547 --> 00:56:26,927
<i>If you have nine sons in a row</i>

861
00:56:27,510 --> 00:56:31,060
<i>Baseball teams make money, you know</i>

862
00:56:31,597 --> 00:56:34,977
<i>Keep your funny side up, up</i>

863
00:56:35,309 --> 00:56:38,849
<i>Let your laughter come through, do</i>

864
00:56:39,647 --> 00:56:43,567
<i>Stand up on your legs,
be like two fried eggs</i>

865
00:56:43,651 --> 00:56:47,151
<i>Keep your sunny side up, up</i>

866
00:56:48,072 --> 00:56:51,082
<i>Keep your sunny side up</i>

867
00:56:52,159 --> 00:56:55,499
It was wonderful to see
my sister and Leonard together.

868
00:56:56,414 --> 00:56:58,174
She drew strength from him,

869
00:57:01,293 --> 00:57:03,343
and they were so much
in love with each other.

870
00:57:04,630 --> 00:57:08,010
She looked happier than she had in years.

871
00:57:09,927 --> 00:57:13,807
I remember they decided
to get married in the spring,

872
00:57:15,766 --> 00:57:17,596
and then, of course, the roof fell in.

873
00:57:19,728 --> 00:57:21,438
NARRATOR: <i>Two weeks before the wedding,</i>

874
00:57:21,522 --> 00:57:25,032
<i>an ex-showgirl named Lita Fox comes forth</i>

875
00:57:25,359 --> 00:57:28,069
<i>and claims that she is married to Zelig.</i>

876
00:57:29,238 --> 00:57:31,488
<i>She also claims to have had his child.</i>

877
00:57:32,116 --> 00:57:34,196
<i>It is an immediate scandal.</i>

878
00:57:38,122 --> 00:57:41,462
We were married a year ago.
He said he was an actor.

879
00:57:41,876 --> 00:57:45,586
He sounded just like one,
and I'm in show business, too.

880
00:57:47,173 --> 00:57:49,593
So we drove to Baltimore
and we were married,

881
00:57:50,134 --> 00:57:51,684
and I have a license to prove it.

882
00:57:52,720 --> 00:57:55,640
NARRATOR: <i>He had married her while
under a different personality.</i>

883
00:57:56,515 --> 00:58:00,095
<i>When she read of the plans for his
forthcoming wedding to Eudora Fletcher,</i>

884
00:58:00,478 --> 00:58:03,478
<i>she was mortified
and decided to take legal action.</i>

885
00:58:04,398 --> 00:58:06,438
<i>Zelig says he will fight it in court,</i>

886
00:58:06,901 --> 00:58:09,951
<i>but public opinion begins
subtly to shift away from him.</i>

887
00:58:11,363 --> 00:58:15,703
<i>Clever attorneys portray Lita Fox
as an abandoned woman.</i>

888
00:58:16,118 --> 00:58:19,038
<i>The child is neglected,
poor and fatherless.</i>

889
00:58:20,372 --> 00:58:23,712
<i>Zelig has sold his life story to Hollywood
for a large sum of money.</i>

890
00:58:24,752 --> 00:58:27,842
<i>When the scandal breaks,
the studio demands its money back.</i>

891
00:58:28,756 --> 00:58:32,636
<i>Zelig can only return half
as the rest has already been spent.</i>

892
00:58:33,594 --> 00:58:38,604
<i>Outraged, the studio gives him half his
life back. They keep the best moments,</i>

893
00:58:39,099 --> 00:58:42,439
<i>and he is left with only
his sleeping hours and mealtimes.</i>

894
00:58:43,395 --> 00:58:47,105
<i>Zelig is shaken by the scandal,
but it is only the beginning.</i>

895
00:58:48,108 --> 00:58:50,369
<i>Now another woman steps forward.</i>

896
00:58:50,444 --> 00:58:53,614
<i>Helen Gray, a salesgirl
from a Wisconsin gift shop</i>

897
00:58:54,031 --> 00:58:56,911
<i>claims that Zelig
is the father of her twins.</i>

898
00:58:57,451 --> 00:59:00,791
<i>She tells her lawyers that he passed
himself off as a fur trapper.</i>

899
00:59:01,956 --> 00:59:03,746
<i>Zelig has no recollection,</i>

900
00:59:04,250 --> 00:59:07,420
<i>but admits it could have happened
when he was under one of his spells.</i>

901
00:59:08,295 --> 00:59:10,505
<i>It is the signal
for the floodgates to open.</i>

902
00:59:11,423 --> 00:59:14,013
He married me up
at the First Church of Harlem.

903
00:59:14,635 --> 00:59:16,795
He told me he was
the brother of Duke Ellington.

904
00:59:17,680 --> 00:59:21,980
He was the guy who smashed my car up.
It was brand-new.

905
00:59:22,810 --> 00:59:25,900
Then he backed up over my mother's wrist.

906
00:59:26,647 --> 00:59:30,187
She's elderly, and uses her wrist a lot.

907
00:59:31,485 --> 00:59:34,235
He painted my house a disgusting color.

908
00:59:35,364 --> 00:59:36,824
He said he was a painter.

909
00:59:37,408 --> 00:59:41,158
I couldn't believe the results.
Then he disappeared.

910
00:59:42,246 --> 00:59:44,536
NARRATOR: <i>That Zelig could be
responsible for the behavior</i>

911
00:59:44,623 --> 00:59:46,833
<i>of each of the personalities he assumed</i>

912
00:59:47,167 --> 00:59:49,207
<i>means dozens of lawsuits.</i>

913
00:59:49,587 --> 00:59:53,507
<i>He is sued for bigamy,
adultery, automobile accidents,</i>

914
00:59:53,591 --> 00:59:56,602
<i>plagiarism, household damages, negligence,</i>

915
00:59:56,677 --> 01:00:00,427
<i>property damages, and performing
unnecessary dental extractions.</i>

916
01:00:02,057 --> 01:00:04,227
I would like to apologize to everyone.

917
01:00:04,310 --> 01:00:07,350
I'm awfully sorry
for marrying all those women.

918
01:00:07,438 --> 01:00:10,518
It just... I don't know,
it just seemed like the thing to do.

919
01:00:11,317 --> 01:00:14,947
And to the gentleman
whose appendix I took out,

920
01:00:15,279 --> 01:00:16,949
I'm... I don't know what to say.

921
01:00:17,031 --> 01:00:20,991
If it's any consolation, I may still
have it somewhere around the house.

922
01:00:23,037 --> 01:00:26,247
My deepest apology goes
to the Trokman family in Detroit.

923
01:00:27,791 --> 01:00:30,541
I... I never delivered a baby before
in my life,

924
01:00:30,628 --> 01:00:35,088
and I, I just thought
that ice tongs was the way to do it.

925
01:00:36,592 --> 01:00:39,972
NARRATOR: <i>Thriving mercilessly
on loopholes and technicalities,</i>

926
01:00:40,054 --> 01:00:42,894
<i>the American legal profession
has a field day.</i>

927
01:00:43,432 --> 01:00:47,732
<i>Zelig is branded a criminal.
Despite Dr. Fletcher's insistence</i>

928
01:00:47,811 --> 01:00:50,197
<i>that he cannot be held
responsible for his actions</i>

929
01:00:50,272 --> 01:00:53,282
<i>while in his chameleon state,
it is no use.</i>

930
01:00:53,901 --> 01:00:57,491
WOMAN:
<i>Leonard Zelig sets a bad moral influence.</i>

931
01:00:58,405 --> 01:01:03,485
<i>America is a moral country.
It's a God-fearing country.</i>

932
01:01:05,120 --> 01:01:06,910
We don't condone scandals,

933
01:01:07,748 --> 01:01:10,418
scandals of fraud and polygamy.

934
01:01:11,960 --> 01:01:14,250
In keeping with a pure society,

935
01:01:15,089 --> 01:01:18,049
I say lynch the little Hebe!

936
01:01:19,677 --> 01:01:21,847
NARRATOR:
<i>Throughout the humiliating ordeal,</i>

937
01:01:21,929 --> 01:01:25,429
<i>Eudora Fletcher stands by
the man she loves, valiantly.</i>

938
01:01:26,809 --> 01:01:31,269
<i>Privately, she tells friends that she is
worried about Zelig's emotional condition,</i>

939
01:01:31,563 --> 01:01:33,741
<i>which seems to her to be deteriorating</i>

940
01:01:33,816 --> 01:01:36,106
<i>under the weight of
conservative moral opinion.</i>

941
01:01:37,486 --> 01:01:40,776
<i>In public, he tries to keep up
an appearance of composure,</i>

942
01:01:40,989 --> 01:01:42,659
<i>but it is increasingly difficult.</i>

943
01:01:43,534 --> 01:01:48,294
<i>It is clear he is coming apart when he and
Eudora Fletcher dine at a Greek restaurant,</i>

944
01:01:48,789 --> 01:01:52,459
<i>and in the midst of the meal,
Zelig begins to turn Greek.</i>

945
01:01:59,508 --> 01:02:04,098
<i>He longs desperately to be liked
once again, to be accepted, to fit in.</i>

946
01:02:05,180 --> 01:02:08,640
<i>Public clamor over his morality
reaches a fever pitch,</i>

947
01:02:08,726 --> 01:02:13,306
<i>and on the eve of his sentencing,
Leonard Zelig vanishes.</i>

948
01:02:21,613 --> 01:02:24,073
<i>This is Chief Inspector
of Police Thomas Dowd</i>

949
01:02:24,241 --> 01:02:26,371
<i>with a national broadcasting news break.</i>

950
01:02:26,535 --> 01:02:29,705
<i>Leonard Zelig is missing.
On the eve of his sentencing</i>

951
01:02:30,122 --> 01:02:32,832
<i>for an assortment
of crimes and misdemeanors</i>

952
01:02:33,250 --> 01:02:35,540
<i>ranging from polygamy to fraud,</i>

953
01:02:36,003 --> 01:02:37,596
<i>he has disappeared.</i>

954
01:02:37,671 --> 01:02:41,341
<i>We are searching for clues and
would appreciate speaking with anyone</i>

955
01:02:41,842 --> 01:02:44,932
<i>who might have any information
leading to his apprehension.</i>

956
01:02:46,180 --> 01:02:49,180
MERYL: <i>My sister was just shattered.</i>

957
01:02:49,850 --> 01:02:54,690
<i>She tried, you know, she tried to keep up
a calm front but she was just too upset.</i>

958
01:02:56,064 --> 01:03:00,614
<i>And she wasn't a person
who usually displayed emotion easily,</i>

959
01:03:01,570 --> 01:03:03,490
<i>except where Leonard was concerned.</i>

960
01:03:07,743 --> 01:03:10,453
NARRATOR:
<i>Dr. Fletcher and the police confer daily.</i>

961
01:03:10,537 --> 01:03:11,964
<i>Together they make public appeals</i>

962
01:03:12,039 --> 01:03:13,959
<i>to anyone who might know
of his whereabouts.</i>

963
01:03:14,875 --> 01:03:18,875
<i>Apart from several crank telephone calls,
there is little response.</i>

964
01:03:19,671 --> 01:03:22,551
<i>Months go by and Zelig is not heard from.</i>

965
01:03:23,091 --> 01:03:26,681
<i>Cars are searched.
False leads pour in from everywhere.</i>

966
01:03:27,554 --> 01:03:29,523
<i>His jacket is recovered in Texas.</i>

967
01:03:29,598 --> 01:03:32,228
<i>A manhunt in that state proves futile.</i>

968
01:03:33,018 --> 01:03:36,188
<i>He is reported seen
in Chicago, in California.</i>

969
01:03:36,814 --> 01:03:40,200
<i>This still photo appears
to have a man resembling him</i>

970
01:03:40,275 --> 01:03:42,315
<i>with a mariachi band in Mexico.</i>

971
01:03:46,740 --> 01:03:49,580
<i>Dr. Fletcher continues
to search for Zelig,</i>

972
01:03:49,701 --> 01:03:52,291
<i>but hopes fade with each passing day.</i>

973
01:03:52,788 --> 01:03:54,578
FLETCHER: <i>All I could think of was Leonard</i>

974
01:03:55,249 --> 01:03:57,419
<i>and how much I missed him and loved him,</i>

975
01:03:58,252 --> 01:04:01,172
<i>and of all the terrific times
we'd spent together.</i>

976
01:04:01,964 --> 01:04:04,764
<i>It was really a very painful time for me.</i>

977
01:04:06,093 --> 01:04:09,723
NARRATOR:
<i>The year ends, and Zelig is still missing.</i>

978
01:04:13,100 --> 01:04:15,020
I just moped around and wept.

979
01:04:15,644 --> 01:04:18,734
And one night, after a very bad time,

980
01:04:19,106 --> 01:04:22,534
my sister Meryl said to me,
"Come on, let's go out for dinner.

981
01:04:22,609 --> 01:04:24,036
"Let's go to a concert."

982
01:04:24,111 --> 01:04:27,451
I said, "No, I can't do it."
But she insisted.

983
01:04:27,948 --> 01:04:30,698
And we went out
and finally ended up in a movie.

984
01:04:31,368 --> 01:04:34,538
<i>We saw</i> Grand Hotel
<i>and with it, there was a newsreel.</i>

985
01:04:44,882 --> 01:04:47,559
MAN: (ON NEWSREEL) <i>Adolf Hitler
and the National Socialist Party</i>

986
01:04:47,634 --> 01:04:50,804
<i>continue to consolidate gains
in Depression-ridden Berlin.</i>

987
01:04:51,597 --> 01:04:53,398
<i>Denouncing the Treaty of Versailles,</i>

988
01:04:53,473 --> 01:04:57,736
<i>the Nazis make fervent appeals to German
patriotism, promising to rebuild...</i>

989
01:04:57,811 --> 01:05:00,811
NARRATOR: <i>Eudora Fletcher
is stunned by what she sees.</i>

990
01:05:01,356 --> 01:05:05,646
<i>Amongst the Brownshirts,
she spots a figure who could be Zelig.</i>

991
01:05:06,653 --> 01:05:09,533
Yes, but then it really made sense,
it made all the sense in the world,

992
01:05:09,656 --> 01:05:14,536
because although he wanted to be loved,
craved to be loved,

993
01:05:14,703 --> 01:05:17,003
there was also something in him

994
01:05:17,080 --> 01:05:21,500
that desired immersion
in the mass and anonymity,

995
01:05:21,793 --> 01:05:25,383
<i>and fascism offered Zelig
that kind of opportunity.</i>

996
01:05:25,756 --> 01:05:28,926
<i>So he could make something
anonymous of himself</i>

997
01:05:29,760 --> 01:05:32,720
<i>by belonging to this vast movement.</i>

998
01:05:34,348 --> 01:05:36,598
NARRATOR:
<i>She sails for Europe the following week.</i>

999
01:05:37,392 --> 01:05:40,152
<i>Ten days later, she arrives in Berlin.</i>

1000
01:05:40,854 --> 01:05:44,194
<i>Germany is a country deep
in the throes of the Depression.</i>

1001
01:05:44,399 --> 01:05:47,189
<i>Militarism and unrest are in the air.</i>

1002
01:05:48,195 --> 01:05:51,695
<i>She searches everywhere and makes
enquiries, but it is impossible.</i>

1003
01:05:52,866 --> 01:05:56,536
<i>After three weeks,
the authorities begin to get suspicious.</i>

1004
01:05:56,954 --> 01:06:00,254
<i>They watch her. While she is out,
they search her hotel room.</i>

1005
01:06:01,375 --> 01:06:05,375
<i>A fourth week goes by,
and she is about to give up and go home,</i>

1006
01:06:05,462 --> 01:06:09,012
<i>when news of a large rally
at Munich catches her attention.</i>

1007
01:06:10,425 --> 01:06:14,845
<i>It is rumored that it will be the largest
gathering to date of Nazi personnel.</i>

1008
01:06:16,181 --> 01:06:20,481
<i>Eudora Fletcher is counting on
the hope that Zelig may also attend.</i>

1009
01:06:20,560 --> 01:06:22,230
<i>And that if she can confront him,</i>

1010
01:06:22,562 --> 01:06:26,022
<i>the strong feeling he has
always had for her can be awakened.</i>

1011
01:06:27,484 --> 01:06:31,994
<i>At first, all appears hopeless.
The crowd is huge,</i>

1012
01:06:32,364 --> 01:06:35,584
<i>and it seems impossible
to locate any one particular face.</i>

1013
01:06:36,201 --> 01:06:39,751
(SPEAKING IN GERMAN)

1014
01:06:50,841 --> 01:06:52,351
NARRATOR: <i>Then, suddenly,</i>

1015
01:06:52,426 --> 01:06:55,176
<i>a figure flanking
the Chancellor captures her attention.</i>

1016
01:06:55,762 --> 01:06:59,432
<i>Behind and to the right of Hitler,
she spots Zelig.</i>

1017
01:07:00,267 --> 01:07:03,687
<i>Struggling to make contact,
she manages to catch his eye.</i>

1018
01:07:04,938 --> 01:07:08,398
<i>Like a man emerging from a dream,
Zelig notices her.</i>

1019
01:07:09,359 --> 01:07:12,239
<i>In a matter of seconds,
everything comes back to him.</i>

1020
01:07:14,406 --> 01:07:17,986
(SPEAKING IN GERMAN)

1021
01:07:24,708 --> 01:07:26,458
(CROWD CHEERING)

1022
01:07:28,962 --> 01:07:32,972
(SPEAKING IN GERMAN)

1023
01:07:35,886 --> 01:07:37,796
(CROWD CHEERING INCREASINGLY LOUDER)

1024
01:07:48,565 --> 01:07:50,605
Leonard! Leonard!

1025
01:07:54,988 --> 01:07:56,198
Leonard!

1026
01:08:11,963 --> 01:08:14,223
It was nothing like
it happened in the movie.

1027
01:08:14,841 --> 01:08:18,141
When Leonard came down from the
podium, they didn't know what to think.

1028
01:08:18,887 --> 01:08:22,467
We couldn't believe our eyes.
Hitler's speech was ruined.

1029
01:08:23,683 --> 01:08:26,023
He wanted to make
a good joke about Poland,

1030
01:08:27,395 --> 01:08:30,765
but just then, Zelig interfered

1031
01:08:31,691 --> 01:08:34,951
and Hitler was extremely upset.

1032
01:08:36,363 --> 01:08:40,703
The SS wanted to grab Zelig,

1033
01:08:41,535 --> 01:08:46,955
but if they would have grabbed him,
they probably would have tortured him,

1034
01:08:47,541 --> 01:08:49,081
or maybe even shot him.

1035
01:08:49,835 --> 01:08:55,755
In the confusion, Fletcher and Zelig got
out of the building through a side door.

1036
01:08:56,466 --> 01:08:59,966
They grabbed a car.
They sped away in the car,

1037
01:09:00,053 --> 01:09:02,353
and the SS after them, shot them...

1038
01:09:04,224 --> 01:09:06,564
NARRATOR: <i>In rare German newsreel footage,</i>

1039
01:09:06,726 --> 01:09:08,936
<i>a quick glimpse
of the escape was recorded.</i>

1040
01:09:11,356 --> 01:09:15,106
(MAN SPEAKING IN GERMAN)

1041
01:09:23,785 --> 01:09:27,245
FLETCHER: <i>I was flying!
It was wonderful. And then...</i>

1042
01:09:27,330 --> 01:09:30,040
Suddenly, something happened.
I was frightened.

1043
01:09:30,417 --> 01:09:33,297
I lost control. We went into a dive.

1044
01:09:33,837 --> 01:09:37,467
Leonard was so terrified
that he changed his personality,

1045
01:09:38,008 --> 01:09:42,758
and before my eyes, because
